The ADC intrinsic noise of 3.8μV/Hz\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$3.8~\upmu\mbox{V}/\sqrt{\mbox{Hz}}$\end{document} is flat (white) down to 10 mHz, below which the ADC 1/f\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$1/f$\end{document} noise becomes visible. Beyond about 8 Hz the ADC quantization noise starts to dominate over the ADC white noise. The FPGA FIR filter will sharply attenuate this noise beyond 40 Hz (80% of the Nyquist frequency) for high 100 Hz output data rate selection. For low 20 Hz data rate, the filter will completely attenuate the quantization noise since the corner frequency is 8 Hz in this case.

