				\begin{document}$\vec{n}_{\mathrm{VBB}}$\end{document} the VBB sensing direction. This allows therefore two testing strategies.

The first one acts on the product gEarthmEarthD→g,Earth\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$g_{\mathrm{Earth}} m_{\mathrm{Earth}} \vec{D}_{g, \mathrm{Earth}}$\end{document} and consists in reducing its norm to the Mars one by adding a mass on the opposite side of the pivot, in order to reduce the larger gravity in such a way that 
				gEarthmEarthDg,Earth=gMarsmMarsDg,Mars.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ g_{\mathrm{Earth}} m_{\mathrm{Earth}} D_{g, \mathrm{Earth}} = g_{\mathrm{Mars}} m_{\mathrm{Mars}} D_{g, \mathrm{Mars}}. $$\end{document}

The second strategy is to tilt the sensor in order to get an Earth gravity projection equal to the Mars one, with the aid of a goniometer (Fig. 81). This can be achieved either by a 19° tilt of the plane defined by the pivot direction and D→g,Earth\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\vec{D}_{g, \mathrm{Earth}}$\end{document} or by tilting the VBB on its side. Two sides of tilting were used. A tilting at 68–70∘\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$68\mbox{--}70^{\circ}$\end{document}, where the tilt direction is in the plane defined by the pivot and gravity and a 32–34∘\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$32\mbox{--}34^{\circ}$\end{document} tilting, where the tilt direction is in a plane with a 60° angle with the pivot, which enable to test two VBBs on Earth. In all these tilting configurations, the precise value of the tilt is depending on the recentering mass, which explains the angular range.

In all these configurations, care must however be taken regarding restoring moment of the VBBs because of the inverted pendulum design. This can be expressed as 
